        "hints": [
            "Use the modulus operator (%) to determine if the number is even or odd.",
            "If the number % 2 equals 0, it is even; otherwise, it is odd."
        ],
        "solutions": [
            {
                "authorID": "4460fe58-54de-4eba-b277-72724d408588",
                "language":"JAVA",
                "title":"Java Even or Odd Solution",
                "segments":[
                    {
                        "title":"Intuition",
                        "desc":"First I remebered that any even integer is divisible by two, but odd integers are one greater than an even integer.",
                        "dataType":"STRING",
                        "data":""
                    },
                    {
                        "title":"Implementation",
                        "desc":"For this problem I used the modulos operator, Math.abs, and an if statement.",
                        "dataType":"STRING",
                        "data":""
                    },
                    {
                        "title":"Implementation",
                        "desc":"",
                        "dataType":"CODE",
                        "data":"class EvenOrOdd { \n   public String isEvenOrOdd(int x) { \n       if(Math.abs(x%2) == 0) \n           return \"Even\"; \n       return \"Odd\"; \n    } \n}"
                    },
                    {
                        "title":"Analysis",
                        "desc":"If the integer 10 is inputted, 10 modulos 2 will return 0, the Math.abs does nothing, but 0 is equal to 0 so the method will return even. If the integer is -9, -9 modulos 2 will return -1, the Math.abs makes this integer a positive 1, since 1 is not equal to 0, the if statement is ignored and the method returns Odd.",
                        "dataType":"STRING",
                        "data":""
                    },
                    {
                        "title":"Complexity",
                        "desc":"This approach has a time complexity of O(1) since the method takes the same amount of operations for any integer.",
                        "dataType":"STRING",
                        "data":""
                    }
                ],
